      <div class="msgHeaderFrame" id="m1289867914314222125">
        <div class="msgSubject">New item suggestion: &quot;Repair Kits&quot;</div>
        <div class="sm notbold">
          
          Posted: 2010-11-15 18:38:34   | <input type="checkbox" name="quote-1289867914314222125" id="quote-1289867914314222125" class="msgQuoteCheck" onchange="multiQuote2()"/><label for="quote-1289867914314222125" onclick="multiQuote2()"> Quote</label>  | <a href="/forum.html?forum=173&amp;mid=1289867914314222125&amp;post=1&amp;replyto=1289867914314222125&amp;page=1" class="icon-replytothis" rel="nofollow">Reply to Post</a> | <a id="FOLLOW_MID_1289867914314222125" onclick="followToggle('add','1289867914314222125')" href="javascript:" class="icon-follow">Follow</a> 
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="msgWhoFrame">
        <div class="msgUM"><a class="msgWhoName Sage" href="/users/BrannonGalvalnor">BrannonGalvalnor</a><div class="msgWhoTitle Sage">Sage</div></div><div class="msgAvatar"></div><div class="msgStar"><img src="http://common.zam.com/shared/s2.gif" alt="*"/></div><div class="msgWhoNum">80 posts</div>
        <div class="msgScore">
          Score: Excellent  
          <div class="msgRatings"></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="msgContentFrame">Given the trouble we have to go through to get our gear repaired to keep it at optimum performance, I thought it'd be a great idea if we can have a new kind of item to help us perform repairs. <br /> <br />Ladies and Gentlemen, I propose to Square Enix that they give us a new item type, <b><u>Repair Kits</b></u>. <br /> <br />Currently, the only ways we can repair our gear is: <br /> <br />1) Do it yourself (you have to have the materials and skill to do it) <br />2) Have a friend do it for you (they have to have the materials and skill to do it) <br />3) Pay the Repair NPC to do it for you (it gets expensive, they only fix gear to 75% durability, and they don't fix jewelry currently) <br />4) Put up your item for repairs and hope someone has the skill, materials, time, and motivation (i.e.: want your reward) to fix your gear <br /> <br />So how about adding some <u>new items</u> that crafters can make and categorize them as <u><b>&quot;Repair Kits&quot;</b></u> and make several varieties.  I suggest the repair kits should have the following properties: <br /> <br />	-Repair kits stack to 12 <br />	-When using a Repair Kit, open a window similar to a synthesis repair window and place (limit of one) the damaged item in for repairs. <br />	-Repair Kits will comprise of one material type and one craft type to repair (i.e. Bronze Blacksmith Repair kit fixes items that require Bronze Nuggets/Ingots and Blacksmith skill while Bronze Armor Repair kit fixes items that require Bronze Plates/Squares/Rings and Armorer skill) <br />	-Limit Durability fixed to 75% and allow the occasional repair attempt with a kit, to fail to keep the demand for crafters to repair gear to a 100% <br />	-Give a small amount of SP for the appropriate craft when an attempt at repairing with a kit is successful <br />	-If the repair attempt is made by an appropriately skilled crafter, allow the repair kit to substitute the material needed and allow for a full 100% durability fix <br />	-Repair Kit creation difficulty scales with the material used (i.e. creating Iron Blacksmith Repair Kits requires more skill than required to make Bronze Blacksmith Repair Kits) <br /> <br />I believe that allowing repair attempts with a kit to fail and limiting fixed durability to 75% should be kept to avoid eliminating the need for skilled crafters to repair goods and is somewhat more realistic.  For example, IRL, when I accidently tear a small, but noticeable hole in my brand new, brandname clothes, it's not practical for me to just throw them away and buy them again. I've very little skill with a needle &amp; thread and I don't have any friends nearby who know how to sow or are professional tailors so sometimes I resign myself to buy one of those cheap sewing kits you find at some local mega-store and I try to patch up the hole.  Usually, I can at least close up the tear (good enough for government work) but if I wanted a real fix for it, I have to seek out friends whom are more skilled at sewing/tailoring or pay some professional to do it for me.  <br /> <br />The other benefits I see in having &quot;Repair Kits&quot; is this would allow people, without the materials nor craft level, to do their own emergency repairs in the field.  Why carry 2 or 3 similar weapons/armor/jewelry when you can just carry a small stack of appropriate repair kits? I'm sure there are some of you who decided to venture out on your own and visit some place you have yet to discover. Maybe you got aggro'd by a monster and beat it down (barely) but now your weapon is damaged and your Anima is awfully low and it's a long walk back, through hostile territory, to the nearest town.  Another scenario where a repair kit would be useful is when you're grinding out that SP and EXP but we all know how quickly weapon durability wears down in a good party.  Wouldn't it be nice to have a repair kit if you or your party members can't repair your weapon?  A lot of hardcore damage dealers want to keep their DPS high and we all know that a damaged weapon is just about as useful at hurting monsters as a styrofoam equivalent. <br /> <br />Other benefits I can see with this new item type is a new market.  Of course, crafters can charge whatever they like and certain rare crafting materials put into repair kits will cost more than others.  And extremely generous crafters can leave their more DoW/DoM oriented friends who lack high crafting skill, a gift of repair kits. <br /> <br /><b><u>TL;DR:</b></u> Create a new item type to allow for a, more <u>convient and portable method</u> for people to have their gear repaired without the need for having leveled the craft, having the materials on hand, or visiting the Repair NPC. <br /> <br />Thoughts?<div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div>Consciousness - That annoying time between naps.</div></div>
